    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_515144256" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/515144256" />
    <a title="Joyce" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6137080-joyce"><img alt="Joyce" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1449204493p2/6137080.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/515144256?book_show_action=true">Jan 23, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joyce" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joyce" href="/user/show/6137080-joyce">Joyce</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6137080-joyce?shelf=foreign-location">foreign-location</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6137080-joyce?shelf=books-read-in-2013">books-read-in-2013</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer515144256" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8638726102343776509">To the End of the Land by David Grossman is a very powerful novel set in the nation of Israel. In this novel, Ora,the mother of 2 sons, decides to go on a hike in the Galilee area after her younger son Offer volunteers for an additional 28 days of service in the Israeli Army. She fears that he will be killed and decides that she will not be home in case officials come to tell her he has been killed. In her mind, she has convinced herself that if she is not home to be informed, then he will be sa</span>
  <span id="freeText8638726102343776509" style="display:none">To the End of the Land by David Grossman is a very powerful novel set in the nation of Israel. In this novel, Ora,the mother of 2 sons, decides to go on a hike in the Galilee area after her younger son Offer volunteers for an additional 28 days of service in the Israeli Army. She fears that he will be killed and decides that she will not be home in case officials come to tell her he has been killed. In her mind, she has convinced herself that if she is not home to be informed, then he will be safe. Recently estranged from her husband Ilan, she forces an old friend and lover, Avram to come with her. She had met Ilan and Avram when they were all teenagers in a hospital. The 3 of them had formed a very close-knit friendship but Ora eventually ended up marrying Ilan. Later Avram is captured in Egypt and brutally tortured during his time as a POW there. When he is brought back to Israel, he has to undergone many surgeries and rehabilitation but even then he remains severe psychologically damaged. As it turns out, Avram is the father of the youngest son but had never wanted anything to do with him. As Ora and Avram hike through the land, Avram undergoes much healing in his spirit and Ora talks to him about Offer. Ora also shares with him about her other son, Adam, who she is also estranged from. For Ora, the sharing about her sons is her way of making them more real for both her and Avram.<br /><br />Although the novel is powerful, I rated it only 2 stars because it was difficult to read through. The plot jumps back and forth in time constantly throughout the book but not in any pattern. Much of the imagery used to convey Ora's feelings is confusing and hard to follow. At times I wondered about her sanity. There were many loose ends in the story as well and the reader is literally left hanging at the end. However, I think some of the difficulty in reading may be due to the novel having been translated from Hebrew. Also, I think cultural differences may contribute to some expressions or descriptions which were difficult to understand.<br /><br />In spite of the negative aspects mentioned above, I am glad I read the book and would still recommend it. However, be forewarned, it is not an easy read! </span>
  <a data-text-id="8638726102343776509" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

